		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Crassus, et Vespasianus Imp. duo peritiss[im]i
						Oeconomi: de illo, Plutarchus in Crasso: de hoc, Suetonius
						in Vespatiano.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Marcus Licinius Crassus"/>
					<person name="Vespasian"/>
					<person name="Plutarch"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Crassus and emperor Vespianus, two most skilled in economics: regarding the former, Plutarchus on Crassus; regarding the latter, Suetonius on Vespatianus.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						Illa ver&ograve; Crassi, Pontij, Balbi Exempla qu&agrave;m pragmatica, et egregia? M. Crassus negebat
						ullam satis magnam pecuniam esse Ei, qui in Rep. Princeps uellet esse, qui suis fructibus exercitu[m]
						alere non posset. C[i]c[er]o Io. Offic. Vtinam, inquit C. Pontius Samnis, ad illa tempora Fortuna
						essem natus, quando Romani
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Marcus Licinius Crassus"/>
					<person name="Lucius Cornelius Balbus"/>
					<person name="Pontius Telesinus"/>
					<person name="Cicero"/>
					<book title="De Officiis"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="M. Crassus"/>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						coepissent: non essem passus
						imperare. 2o Offi.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>How pragmatic and distinguished are those examples of Crassus, Pontius, and Balbus? Marcus Crasses denied that there was any big sum of money sufficient for him; he who wished
			to be prince in the Republic, who could not nourish an army from his income. Cicero, book 1 of 'De Officiis'. If only, said C. Pontius, [leader] of the Samnites, I were born in those times by Fortune,
			when the Romans had begun [to accept bribes]: I would not have suffered [them] to rule. Book 2 of 'De Officiis'.</translation> <!--JG: Harvey didn't copy Cicero's lines completely, hence a literal translation wouldn't have made sense-->
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						Cornelius Balbus apud
						Velleium; ausus est ingredi Castra hostium; et cum ipso Consule sa[e]p&egrave; conferre, Quanti se venderet?
						Vnde poste&agrave; magnus apud Ca[e]sarem, reru[m] Dominu[m]. Vna Ca[e]sarianaru[m] artium. Largitio. 
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Lucius Cornelius Balbus"/>
					<person name="Marcus Velleius Paterculus"/>
					<book title="Roman History"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>Cornelius Balbius in Velleius; he was prepared to advance into the fort of the enemy to confer often with the consul himself: what price to put on himself?
			Thereafter he was great before Caesar, the master of things. One skilled in the arts of emperors. Bribery.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
